sentence: June Federal estimates for payrolls are in hand.
The U.S. added +288K jobs last month.
The U.S. unemployment rate hit 6.1%, a six-year low.
Nearly all industries added jobs in June.
The 10-year U.S. Treasury rate jumped on the news.
Stock markets saw it coming on Wednesday.
May jobs moved up to +224K from an earlier estimate of +217K.
April jobs moved up to a whopping +304K jobs from +282K.
Yes gang, that's a 3-handle number.
Wages are up +2% over the past 12 months.
The CPI moves in lock step with that number.
The Fed has a 2% inflation target.
So the underlying labor market is in that 'Goldilocks' state with respect to wage pressure.
The U.S. economy is now on a five month long roll racking up monthly job adds above +200K.
In 2014, this U.S. economy has produced an average of +231K jobs a month.
That's 19% faster than 2013.
My RTI question: Is the "Muddle Through" Economy Behind Us?
